\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 Where does the chaos come from?\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs22 \cf2 \
By linking the output of every thread to the input of the next in a circular arrangement (last to first) we create a state of interdependence. By sharing memory between threads, we introduce race conditions where order of memory access will affect the result of the content.\
\
With the race conditions, we don\'92t know if the rotation happened after or before the addition, or was it the xor this time? Or maybe I write over the fresh xor with my rotated old value\'85 ICM does this constantly.\
\
